{
  "answer": "**The corpus contains gnomic verse and wisdom aphorisms (proverbs/maxims) in *Old English Elegies*, specifically its chapter \"Maxims I\" (Chapter 6).**[^1]\n\nThis chapter is a classic example of Anglo-Saxon gnomic poetry—a collection of loosely connected wise sayings, proverbs, and reflections on life, society, fate, morality, and the natural world (e.g., \"Wise men should exchange sayings\"; \"A good name is best\"; \"Frost must freeze, fire melt wood\").[^2][^3] It exemplifies the genre through its terse, aphoristic style and themes of proper conduct, the transience of life, and divine order.[^4]\n\n**No works in the corpus contain riddles.** Searches returned only metaphorical uses of \"riddle\" in Urdu poetry (*Bang-E-Dara Part 1* by Allama Iqbal and *Diwan-E-Ghalib* by Mirza Ghalib), not actual riddle poems.[^5][^6]\n\n**Other notes:**\n- *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* (Chapter 3) briefly mentions \"aphorisms\" (sūtras) as part of Vedic literature but does not contain them as a structural element.[^7]\n- No other works match these categories. The Smṛti texts (e.g., *Manusmṛti*, *Nāradasmṛti*) are dharmaśāstra law codes in verse but not primarily gnomic or aphoristic collections. Cynewulf's poems (*Andreas*, *Elene*, *Juliana*) are hagiographic narratives without these forms.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 6: Maxims I](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/).\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 6: Maxims I](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-84cf09).\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 6: Maxims I](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/#p-4bfdc5).\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 6: Maxims I](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/06-maxims-i/translation/).\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [Chapter 44: Zuhd aur Rindi](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-5cbc5a).\n[^6]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [Chapter 44: Gar khamoshi se faida ikhfa-e-haal hai](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/44-gar-khamoshi-se-faida-ikhfa-e-haal-hai/translation/#p-710e03).\n[^7]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, [Chapter 3](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/03/translation/#p-55d67a).",
